   923→#### Example
   924→
   925→```js
   926→import ky, {isForceRetryError} from 'ky';
  1000→### HTTPError
  1001→
  1002→Exposed for `instanceof` checks. The error has a `response` property with the [`Response` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Response), `request` property with the [`Request` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request), and `options` property with normalized options (either passed to `ky` when creating an instance with `ky.create()` or directly when performing the request).
  1046→### TimeoutError
  1047→
  1048→The error thrown when the request times out. It has a `request` property with the [`Request` object](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/Request).
  1050→## Tips
  1051→
  1052→### Sending form data
  1053→
  1054→Sending form data in Ky is identical to `fetch`. Just pass a [`FormData`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/FormData) instance to the `body` option. The `Content-Type` header will be automatically set to `multipart/form-data`, overriding any existing `Content-Type` header.
  1080→#### Modifying FormData in hooks
  1081→
  1082→If you need to modify FormData in a `beforeRequest` hook (for example, to transform field names), delete the `Content-Type` header before creating a new `Request`:
  1109→### Setting a custom `Content-Type`
  1110→
  1111→Ky automatically sets an appropriate [`Content-Type`](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Type) header for each request based on the data in the request body. However, some APIs require custom, non-standard content types, such as `application/x-amz-json-1.1`. Using the `headers` option, you can manually override the content type.
  1129→### Cancellation
  1130→
  1131→Fetch (and hence Ky) has built-in support for request cancellation through the [`AbortController` API](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/API/AbortController). [Read more.](https://developers.google.com/web/updates/2017/09/abortable-fetch)
  1156→### Proxy support (Node.js)
  1157→
  1158→#### Native proxy support
  1159→
  1160→Node.js 24.5+ supports automatic proxy configuration via environment variables. Set `NODE_USE_ENV_PROXY=1` or use the `--use-env-proxy` CLI flag.
  1177→#### Using ProxyAgent
  1178→
  1179→For more control, use `ProxyAgent` or `EnvHttpProxyAgent` with the `dispatcher` option.
  1209→### HTTP/2 support (Node.js)
  1210→
  1211→Undici supports HTTP/2, but it's not enabled by default. Create a custom dispatcher with the `allowH2` option:
  1249→### Consuming Server-Sent Events (SSE)
  1250→
  1251→Use [`parse-sse`](https://github.com/sindresorhus/parse-sse):
  1264→### Extending types
  1265→
  1266→Ky's TypeScript types are intentionally defined as type aliases rather than interfaces to prevent global module augmentation, which can lead to type conflicts and unexpected behavior across your codebase. If you need to add custom properties to Ky's types like `KyResponse` or `HTTPError`, create local wrapper types instead:
  1292→## FAQ
  1293→
  1294→#### How do I use this in Node.js?
  1295→
  1296→Node.js 18 and later supports `fetch` natively, so you can just use this package directly.
  1298→#### How do I use this with a web app (React, Vue.js, etc.) that uses server-side rendering (SSR)?
  1299→
  1300→Same as above.
  1302→#### How do I test a browser library that uses this?
  1303→
  1304→Either use a test runner that can run in the browser, like Mocha, or use [AVA](https://avajs.dev) with `ky-universal`. [Read more.](https://github.com/sindresorhus/ky-universal#faq)
  1306→#### How do I use this without a bundler like Webpack?
  1307→
  1308→Make sure your code is running as a JavaScript module (ESM), for example by using a `<script type="module">` tag in your HTML document. Then Ky can be imported directly by that module without a bundler or other tools.
  1321→#### How is it different from [`got`](https://github.com/sindresorhus/got)
  1322→
  1323→Got is maintained by the same people as Ky, so you probably want Ky instead. It's smaller, works in the browser too, and is more stable since it's built on Fetch.
  1325→#### How is it different from [`axios`](https://github.com/axios/axios)?
  1326→
  1327→See my answer [here](https://twitter.com/sindresorhus/status/1037763588826398720).
  1329→#### How is it different from [`r2`](https://github.com/mikeal/r2)?
  1330→
  1331→See my answer in [#10](https://github.com/sindresorhus/ky/issues/10).
  1333→#### What does `ky` mean?
  1334→
  1335→It's just a random short npm package name I managed to get. It does, however, have a meaning in Japanese:
  1339→## Browser support
  1340→
  1341→The latest version of Chrome, Firefox, and Safari.
  1343→## Node.js support
  1344→
  1345→Node.js 18 and later.
  1347→## Related
  1348→
  1349→- [fetch-extras](https://github.com/sindresorhus/fetch-extras) - Useful utilities for working with Fetch
  1350→- [ky-hooks-change-case](https://github.com/alice-health/ky-hooks-change-case) - Ky hooks to modify cases on requests and responses of objects
  1352→## Maintainers
  1353→
  1354→- [Sindre Sorhus](https://github.com/sindresorhus)
  1355→- [Seth Holladay](https://github.com/sholladay)
  1356→- [Szymon Marczak](https://github.com/szmarczak)
